[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ How should Black respond to 3. e5?   There are only a few basic strategies on which all systems regularly played by Black are build.   Before looking at these strategies, let us first consider the fundamental characteristics of this position. The most obvious is that the center is closed and none of the central pawns can move and that White controls more space.   In such positions, one of the first questions to ask is which bishops are good  (not hindered by blocked pawns of their color)  and which are bad. More generally you should check which pieces will have difficulties to find good squares. White's 'bad bishop' is the one on  c1  but it still has plenty of squares to choose from, and it will have  (in many variations)  the important role of protecting  d4  , usually from  e3  or  b2  .   Black's bad bishop is the bishop on  c8  . It currently has only one square available. But there are two other pieces with a potential problem. The bishop on  f8  and the knight on  g8  . Although the bishop on  f8  is the good bishop, it will, after White plays the standard move c3, only have one safe square to develop to: the square  e7  . Unfortunately for Black, the same is true for the knight on  g8  . The only safe square at the moment is the square  e7  . On  h6  it can be taken by the bishop on  c1  which will lead to an ugly double h-pawn. We will later see that there are situations in which  h6  is, in fact, a good square for the knight even if it can be taken and that especially if Black castles queenside the doubled pawn may not be bad at all.  Now we can go back to the original question. How should Black respond. All systems regular played by Black can be understood in the context of the preceding paragraphs.   The first group of systems tries to exchange the bishop on  c8  for its counterpart on  f1  . Usually Black does that by either playing b7-b6 and Bc8-a6 at some point or by protecting the square  b5  by either Qd8-b6 or a7-a6, followed by Bc8, Bd7 and Bb5. These systems are all playable but we will not discuss them here. I play some of them occasionally, but my impression is that they don't put enough pressure on White. White usually gets a comfortable game with a stable space advantage. But the idea of exchanging the bad bishop is one Black needs to keep in mind in all variations.   The second group of systems tries to put pressure on  d4  immediately with the moves c7-c5, Nb8-c6 and Qd8-b6. I play these systems regularly, and I like them, but the amount of theory has grown quite a bit, and usually the White players are well prepared for them.   The third group of systems takes a slower, more flexible approach. Black puts some pressure on  d4  , but also tries to complete development as quickly as possible. These are the system c7-c5, Nb8-c6 and Ng8-e7 and the system c7-c5, Nb8-c6 and Bc8-d7. I find the first of these two systems not so easy to play. So the set-up I recommend here is the second system with Bd7.   In the Bd7 system Black tries to solve the problem of the traffic jam on  e7  (what piece to put there)  by playing an early f6. If White takes on  f6  then either the knight can take back leaving  e7  and also  d6  for the bishop. If White does not take, then Black usually captures on  e5  at a moment where White is forced to take back with a pawn  (possible after some pieces have been exchanged on e5)  . After that Black can play Ne7-g6 putting pressure on  e5  and leaving  e7  for the bishop or Nh6-f7  (nor more f-pawn)  and Be7.   Of course, there are many exceptions and special cases we need to consider but the fundamental ideas are just this. }
3... c5
{ Black attacks the pawn on  d4  . If Black manages to exchange this pawn, then White's pawn on  e5  loses some support and Black gains the new square  c5  for the bishop. }
4. c3
{ The most common and indeed, the best move. The first three chapters discuss a variety of other moves. The most important of these are:    (i)  4. Nf3 aiming for quick development and sacrificing the pawn on  d4  ,    (ii)  4. Qg4 an old move by Nimzowitsch which can be dangerous if handled incorrectly and    (iii)  4. dxc5 White does not want to be bothered with defending the pawn on  d4  . This last move is not very challenging for Black.   There are two more moves often played by less experienced players. 4. Bb5 and 4. f4. The first either loses time if White retreats with the bishop after the check or gives Black for free what several Black systems work very hard to achieve: the exchange of the bad bishop. The second protects  e5  but solves Black's problem with the square  e7  . Now  h6  is a safe place for the black knight, the bishop on  c1  does not cover  h6  any longer, and the knight can move to  f5  to put extra pressure on  d4  anytime. }
4... Nc6 5. Nf3
{ Again the most common and also most certainly the best move. Alternatives are considered in chapter 4. Among those there is only one move I encounter regularly, and that is 5. Be3 the Kupreichik variation. Here Black has two good responses. See chapter 4 for details. }
5... Bd7
{ We finally arrived at the starting point of the Nc6, Bd7 system  (sometimes also called the Euwe system)  . Again White has several options in this position. The less common options are covered in chapter 5. And chapters 6-9 each cover one of the more common options: 6. dxc5, 6. a3, 6. Be2 and 6. Bd3. Among these, I believe 6. Be2 is strongest. But 6. Bd3 can be the most dangerous option if you are not sufficiently prepared. }
*

