[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "Move Guide"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5
{ I would not advise you to read the guide in one go. Just look at it when you have difficulties in deciding what to do with a specific piece. None of the rules below is absolute, they are rather a summary of what is in the back of my mind when playing the Advance Variation.   1 Pawns.  ═══════  1.1 cxd4 and dxc5  ─────────────────    • Black should wait with cxd4 until either      + the White knight on  b1  has moved so that Nb1-c3 is no longer possible      + White is threatening dxc5    • White should avoid dxc5 unless      +  d4  cannot be defended any longer      + there is a bishop on  e3  and White can force the exchange of the dark-squared bishops      + White wants to play Bd3 and O-O and playing Bd3 without dxc5 would lose the pawn on  d4   1.2 c5-c4  ─────────    • should only be considered after White has played a3 because, if the a-pawn is still on  a2  , then c4 / b3 cxb3 / axb3 followed by c4 is usually very good for White  1.3 f2-f4  ─────────    • often a bad move    • allows Black to play Nh6 without having to worry about Bxh6    •  e3  is often weak  1.4 f7-f6  ─────────    • if White takes on  f6  and Black plays Nxf6, then Black gets positions similar to the Tarrasch Variation but with extra tempi    • recapture with the g-pawn is usually also good  1.5 g7-g5  ─────────    • often together with h7-h6 or f7-f6 especially if Black castles queenside    • can sometimes be played for tactical reasons because the knight has to defend  d4  or  e5   
2 Knights.  ═════════  2.1 Nb8  ───────  The knight on  b8     • almost always goes to  c6     • can go to  d7  in the 4. Nf3 system    • also goes to  c4  via  a5  in the Kupreichik variation and after 6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. b4   2.2 Ng8  ───────  Possible moves for the knight on  g8  are    • Ngxf6 after f6 / exf6    • Ne7 -> can continue to  g6  ,  c6  or  f5       + if the knight on  c6  has been exchanged then Ne7-c6 is most common      + with a knight on  c6  and a white pawn on  d4  , Ne7-f5 most common      + with a knight on  c6  and a white pawn on  e5  but none on  d4  , Ne7-g6 is most common    • Nh6 often involves castling queenside like in the 6. Be2 f6 or 6. a3 f6 variation      + need to consider Bxh6      + usually a good move after White has played f4  (avoids the trouble with the e7 square)     • Nh6-f5  (avoids e7)     • Nh6-f7  (only possible after the f pawn has moved)  , puts pressure on  e5  , prepares g5  2.3 Ng1  ───────  Possible moves for the knight on  g1  are    • Nf3 essentially the only move, defending both  d4  and  e5   2.4 Nb1  ───────  The knight on  b1     • often stays on  b1  for a bit in the 4. c3 system.     • develops to  c3  after cxd4 cxd4 has been played. There it      • blocks the c-file      • stops Bb5      • may threaten Nb5 or Na4 to drive away the black queen    • usually goes to  d2  and then  b3  to recapture on  d4  in the 4. Nf3 system   
3 Bishops.  ═════════  3.1 Bc8  ───────  The bishop on  c8     • is Black's bad bishop    • almost always goes to  d7  (in this repertoire)  to make room for the rook    • goes on to  b5  to be exchanged or to  a4  in the 'a3 c4' variations    • comes to life after  f6  via  d7  and  e8   3.2 Bf8  ───────  The bishop on  f8     • most of the time goes to  e7  , sometimes after a check on  b4     • often goes to  c5  as well in the 4. Nf3 system     • can even use the route Bb4-a5-c7 to put pressure on  e5  in the 4. Nf3 system    • can go to  g7  if Nh6 / Bxh6 or an early g5 by Black has been played    • may sometimes win a pawn by playing Bxa3 but this weakens the dark squares  (dangerous for Black)   3.3 Bf1  ───────  The bishop on  f1     • usually is best placed on  d3  but often settles for  e2  for tactical reasons    • should not go to  b5  unless there are concrete reasons  3.4 Bc1  ───────  The bishop on  c1     • is White's bad bishop    • usually goes to  b2  after a3 and b4, or to  e3  if White still has pawns on  d4  and  e5     • often goes to  f4  to protect  e5  in the variations without 4. c3  The move    • Bb2 may allow tactics if the bishop is unprotected  (Na5 with Qb6 and white pawn on b4)     • Be3 is a bit passive and allows Nf5xe3    • Bxh6 is double-edged. It      + is usually a bad idea if Black can play Qxb2 unless Black's queen can be captured after taking the rook on  a1       + weakens Black's pawn structure           + gives Black the bishop pair and open files on the kingside  (good with O-O-O by Black)   
4 Other Pieces.  ══════════════  4.1 Qd8  ───────  The black queen usually goes to    •  b6  to put pressure on  b2  and  d4     •  c7  to put pressure on  e5  if Black has played  f6     •  a5  in the 4. Qg4 variation  4.2 Ke1  ───────  The white king    • usually castles short    • sometimes goes to  f1  after Bb4+ to keep  d4  protected  4.3 Ke8  ───────  The black king    • often castles long in the  f6  variations    • often stays in the center  
5 Other Considerations.  ════════  5.1 square  e7  (Be7 vs Ne7)   ──────────────────────────  The square  e7     • is needed by the dark-squared bishop and the knight on  g8     • may be the last escape square for both a black bishop on  b4  and a knight on  f5     • is used in the 4. c3 systems usually first by the knight and only after finding and securing a spot on  g6  ,  f5  or even  c6  for the knight it is the bishop's turn to go to  e7 }
*

