[White "2. Various 4th Moves"]
[Black "Introduction to 4. Qg4 and other rarely played 4th Moves"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5
{ This first chapter discusses the alternatives to the mainline 4. c3 and the relatively popular sidelines 4. Nf3 and 4. dxc5. }
4. Qg4
{ This is the most important of the sidelines covered in this chapter. The line suggested for Black is also very concrete and leads to at least a small advantage for Black.   Most of the other moves can be handled using a few rules of thumb:   -take quickly on  d4  to isolate  e5  ,  -put pressure on  e5  ,    -f4 can be answered by Nh6 if the knight hasn't yet moved,  -Bb5 is not dangerous, both Bd7 and Nc6 are good answers, with Nc6 generally leading to the more complex positions,  -after Bf4 consider Qb6,      -don't take on  d4  while White can still set up his pieces similar to the Steinitz variation in the French: f4, Nf3, Nbd2, Nb3, Nxd4, Be3.  The first two moves are similar to reasonable variations, the Wing-Gambit and the Kupreichik variation,  but there are concrete reasons why they don't work as well as their counterparts.    4.b4  cxd4  5.a3  a5  6.b5  Nd7  Here the first move is essential. Do not take on  b4  because White can play a3 and regardless of whether you take on  a3  or whether you let White take on  b4  a subsequent c3 by White will give White a very stable center.    4.Be3  cxd4  5.Bxd4  Nc6  6.c3  Nge7  7.f4  g5  Here the key idea is that at move 5 White will have to take on  d4  with either bishop or queen, neither of which is well-placed there. This line has not been chosen for its theoretical merit, but for the large number of typical manoeuvers for Black in the subsequent variations which make studying these lines worthwhile.     The next two variations aim for a setup similar to the Steinitz variation. White plans to put   -a pawn on  f4  ,   -the knights on  f3  and  d4  and   -the dark-squared bishop on  e3  .   Here it is a good idea to wait with the capture on  d4  until White can no longer reach such a setup.       4.f4  Nc6  5.Nf3  Nh6  Here Black will continue with moves like Bd7, Rc8, Qb6 and Nf5. Black does not have to play cxd4 anytime soon because White cannot play dxc5. After Bxc5 the weakness of the diagonal  a7  -  g1  would be a problem for White.       4.Nd2  Nc6  5.Ngf3  cxd4  Black should take on  d4  as soon as the Steinitz setup is no longer possible.     The final two moves also show up from time to time.      4.Bb5+  Here anything reasonable is fine for Black, Bd7 is very safe, Nc6 may give better winning chances.      4.Bf4  Qb6  5.Nd2  Nc6  6.Ngf3  Qxb2  Here I believe waiting until Nf3 has been played before playing Qxb2 is better than taking immediately because with the knight still on  g1  the move Ne2 can be a bit unpleasant. }
4... Nc6
{ Qa5 is playable directly as well, but inserting the knight moves has two concrete advantages:   -the black queen on  a5  is protected,   -the white queen on  g4  cannot return to  d1  . }
5. Nf3 Qa5+ 6. Bd2
{ Here White has a couple of alternatives:     6.c3  cxd4  In this line, Black wins a pawn.    6.Kd1  Bd7  Here Black can develop and then open the center to make use of the misplaced white king.    6.Nc3  a6  Black has to prevent Nb5 but then develops usually. }
6... Qb6
{ Black is a bit better. The next moves will be, in most cases, Nh6 and Nxd4 or Nf5. }
*

