[Black "4. b4 7. f4 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. b4
{ This is an inferior version of the Wing Gambit 1. e4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e5 c5 4. b4 since Black can take on  d4  here. I only included this move since Watson discusses it. }
4... cxd4 { Black gains a tempo by attacking  b4  . } 5. a3 a5
{ To get control of  c5  . } 6. b5 Nd7
{ Black puts pressure on  e5  and keeps an eye on  c5  . } 7. f4 f6
{ The most principled move.  The quiet   7...Nh6  followed by Nc5, a4, Bd7 and either Ne4 or Nf5 is also good for Black. }
8. Bd3 Qc7
{ Black wants to destroy White's center at all costs.   8...Nh6  is less ambitious but also good for Black. }
9. exf6
{ 9.Qh5+  has to be checked as well. After  g6  10.Bxg6  hxg6  11.Qxh8  Qxc2!  Black is winning.   12.Nd2  Nc5  13.Qxg8  otherwise Black plays Nd3+ and Nh6 with a more than enough compensation for the exchange.  13...Bd7  14.a4  Nd3+  15.Ke2  Nxf4+  16.Kf2  O-O-O  Black is winning with Nd3+, Bc5 and fxe5 coming next.   12.Bd2  Nc5  13.Qxg8  Bd7  14.a4  If White allows Bxb5 then the game is over very soon.  Nd3+  15.Ke2  Nxf4+  16.Kf2  fxe5  with move like O-O-O, Bc5, e4 coming up White won't survive for long.   12.Ne2  d3  Black is winning. }
9... Ngxf6 10. Nf3 Bd6
{ Black will castle next. After castling, Black can choose among many possible continuations. For example:   (i)  play e5 immediately,    (ii)  prepare e5 with Re8 and then e5, or   (iii)  play Nc5 to protect  e6  and to prepare Ne4. }
