1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Be3 cxd4
{ Playing Nc6 would allow White to transpose to the Kupreichik variation after 5. c3. In this position, Black can be more ambitious. }
5. Qxd4
{ It is not clear why White played Be3 if he takes back with the queen here. }
5... Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd7 7. Bxc6 bxc6
{ Black has a mobile pawn center, the bishop pair and a nice target on  e5  . Defending the pawn on  e5  with f4 restricts White's dark-squared bishop even further. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Various 4th Moves"]
[Black "4. Be3 5. Qxd4 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Be3 cxd4
{ Playing Nc6 would allow White to transpose to the Kupreichik variation after 5. c3. In this position, Black can be more ambitious. }
5. Qxd4
{ It is not clear why White played Be3 if he takes back with the queen here. }
5... Nc6 6. Qf4 Nge7
{ A typical response to Qf4. Black prepares to attack  e5  again with tempo. }
7. Bd3 Qc7
{ Black can play Ng6 as well. Then White has to exchange his bishop with Bxg6 to save  e5  . The bishop pair and the half-open h-file will give a small advantage in that case. But after Nf3 the pawn on  e5  will be no longer weak.  The move Qc7 tries for more. This time White cannot get rid of any of the attackers. If White plays Bb5 to pin the knight Black has Ng6 and now Bxg6 is no longer possible. So Nf3 is the only move for White. }
8. Nf3 f6
{ This forces White to take on  f6  giving Black complete control of the center. }
9. exf6 Qxf4 10. Bxf4 gxf6
{ Black is better since White cannot prevent e5. White will have difficulties keeping Black's pawn center under control. }
*

