[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Various 4th Moves"]
[Black "4. Be3 7. Bd3 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Be3 cxd4
{ Playing Nc6 would allow White to transpose to the Kupreichik variation after 5. c3. In this position Black can be more ambitious. }
5. Bxd4 Nc6 6. c3 Nge7 7. Bd3 Nxd4 8. cxd4 Nc6
{ The second knight comes to  c6  to put pressure on  d4  and to make room for the bishop on  f8  . Now all of Black's minor pieces find good squares. }
9. Nf3 Qb6 10. Qd2 Bd7 11. Be2 g5
{ Here Black has a good alternative in   11...Rc8  followed by Na5 and Nc4, but g5 is more entertaining. The pawn cannot be taken without allowing Black to take on d4. Since Black also threatens to drive away the support for d4 with g4 White's response is forced. }
12. h3 Nxd4
{ Moves like Be7 or O-O-O are a bit better for Black as well. But the piece sacrifice Nxd4 gives Black two pawns and a strong attack. }
13. Nxd4 { Qxd4 would also be met by Bc5 and Bxf2+. } 13... Bc5
{ The idea of Nxd4. The knight has to move, and the pawn on  f2  falls with check. }
14. Nb3 { Other knight moves are no better. } 14... Bxf2+ 15. Kf1 Bg3
{ Here we see the reason for including the moves g5 and h3. Black can use the square g3 for the bishop. Black is winning. Black can even spend time on playing a5 and a4 to chase the knight away. Bf4 is also always a threat. And finally, it is worth pointing out that White cannot exchange queens with Qd4 because after the exchange the two pawns  e5  and  b2  will fall, giving Black four pawns for the piece. }
*

