1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Be3 cxd4
{ Playing Nc6 would allow White to transpose to the Kupreichik variation after 5. c3. In this position, Black can be more ambitious. }
5. Bxd4 Nc6 6. c3 Nge7 7. f4 g5
{ The move g5 exploits the weakness of the  c1  -  h6  diagonal. Black temporarily sacrifices a pawn but gets complete control of the dark squares in return. Instead   7...Nxd4  8.cxd4  Bd7  9.Nf3  Qb6  10.Qd2  Rc8  11.Nc3  Nc6  12.Be2  Be7  13.O-O  O-O =  is about equal. }
8. fxg5 h6 9. gxh6 Nxd4 10. cxd4 Qb6
{ The simplest solution. Both Bd7 and Bh6 are attractive as well, but showing that Bh6 or Bd7 is at least a little bit better for Black proved to be too difficult for me. So I had to look for alternatives and Qb6 seems to do the job. }
11. Nc3 Bd7 12. h7
{ White plays h7 to make use of the h-pawn one last time before it is taken. A rook on  h7  can be a useful target for either a queen or bishop on  d3  , by either just winning a tempo for White or by pinning any knight which dares to move to  f5  . }
12... Rxh7 13. Qd3 Nf5 14. Nge2 Rh4 15. g4
{ This is White's only chance. If White plays O-O-O, then Ne3 is strong, and if White plays Rd1, then Black can castle. }
15... Rxg4 16. Bh3 Rxd4 17. Nxd4
{ White wins the exchange, but Black gets the bishop pair, and strong passed pawns. }
17... Qxd4 18. Bxf5 Qxe5+ 19. Kd1 Qxf5 20. Qxf5 exf5
{ The two bishops are strong, and it will be difficult for White to stop Black's d- and f-pawn. Black is a bit better. }
