1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nd2 Nc6 5. Ngf3 cxd4 6. Nb3 Qc7 7. Nbxd4 Nxe5
{ Taking on  e5  seems risky, but turns out to be fine for Black. } 8. Bf4
{ this looks like White's best try. } 8... Nxf3+ 9. Qxf3 Qa5+ 10. c3 a6 11. Bd3
Nf6 12. O-O Be7 13. Rfe1 Qd8
{ This move protects the bishop and prepares to castle.   13. ...O-O  14.Nf5  exf5  15.Rxe7  Ne4  is unclear. }
14. Bc2 O-O
{ Black is still behind in development, but I don't believe White has sufficient compensation. Black has several plans:   1  Complete development with Bd7, Rc8.   2  Exchange pieces with Bd6. If White responds with Bg5, then Black can play h6 since the exchange on  f6  is not a problem. But I prefer to keep my dark-squared bishop in such positions.  3  If White's attack gets too dangerous then returning the pawn with Ne4 to neutralize White's light-squared bishop is also an option. }
15. Qg3 Nh5 16. Qd3 g6 17. Bh6 Re8
{ It is not clear to me what compensation for the pawn White has. } *

