[Black "4. Qg4 Qa5 Info"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Qg4 Qa5+
{ This is also an interesting move with similar ideas to our main line. The variations below show that playing 4. ... Nc6 5. Nf3 before the queen check can help Black in a few lines. The coverage below is not meant to be exhaustive. }
5. Bd2 Nh6
{ Black has an alternative:   5. ...Qb6  6.Nc3  Nh6   6. ...cxd4  7.Nb5  h5  8.Qxd4  Bc5  9.Qf4  a6  10.b4  axb5  11.bxc5  Qxc5  12.Bb4  White has the initiative.  7.dxc5  Qxb2  8.Qd1  Without the knight on  f3  (, White can return with the queen to rescue his remaining queenside pawns. This position is unclear as long as Black does not make the mistake)  Bxc5??  9.Rb1  Qa3  10.Rb3  Qa5  11.Ne4  Qc7  12.Nxc5  Qxc5  13.Rc3  and White wins. }
6. Qxe6+ fxe6 7. Bxa5
{ Here it is easy to see why knights on  f3  and  c6  would benefit Black. The bishop on  a5  could be captured. }
7... Bd7 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. Bc3 Rc8
{ Black has enough compensation for the pawn. The pawns on  d4  ,  e5  ,  c2  and even  f2  if White plays dxc5 are all easy targets. So Black should be able to regain the pawn if he wants. }
*

