[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. 4. dxc5"]
[Black "Introduction to 4. dxc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. dxc5
{ This is not a very logical move, but it shows up from time to time. The executive summary would be: play Nc6, Bxc5 and then either f6 or Nge7.   A slightly more detailed summary would add two more points  -if Bf4 is played early, check if Qb6 is good,  -play f6 if White has played Nf3 and this threatens to win a pawn on  e5  , otherwise, play Nge7. }
4... Nc6
{ 4...Bxc5  5.Qg4  is not dangerous for Black, but recapturing on  c5  immediately just gives White extra options. So my suggestion is to stick to 4...Nc6. }
5. Nf3
{ 5. Bf4 and 5. Bb5 have been played as well. Neither is particularly good. }
5... Bxc5 6. Bd3 f6 7. exf6
{ 7.Qe2  fxe5  8.Nxe5  Nxe5  9.Qe5  Nf6  is also good for Black, who threatens Bxf2 already. The queen on  e5  will be later chased away with Bd6 or Ng4, after which Black can play e5 with a good position. }
7... Nxf6 8. O-O O-O { Black is already slightly better. } *

