[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. 4. Nf3"]
[Black "Introduction to 4. Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3
{ Currently Nc6 is the most popular answer, but I prefer Eingorn's suggestion also recommended by Berg, and Aagaard and Ntirlis to take immediately on  d4  . The idea is to put the knights on  d7  and  c6  to put pressure on  e5  . It also avoids any move order tricks after Nc6 5. c3 in case you want to play a system without Nc6 against 4. c3 }
4... cxd4 5. Bd3
{ 5.Qxd4  Nc6  In many of the resulting positions White has to give his light-squared bishop for a knight on either  c6  or  g6  to reduce the pressure on  e5  . Exchanging the best attacking piece  (among White's minor pieces)  usually means that Black has at least equalized.   If the exchange happens on  c6  , then Black has often the choice between recapturing with a pawn which strengthens the center and makes Ba6 possible or to recapture with a piece. If the exchange happens on  g6  , Black usually takes back with the h-pawn opening the h-file and enabling rook lifts, e.g. Rh5 to put additional pressure on  e5  .    5.Nxd4  Nc6  followed by Ne7 and Ng6 and Black is fine. }
5... Nd7
{ This is the reason why Black has to play cxd4 first. The other knight on  g8  should go to  c6  to put extra pressure on  e5  and solves Black's development problems: the dark-squared bishop will not be hindered by a knight on  e7  . Note that this works because there is no d-pawn defending  e5  as in the Tarrasch Variation, and that Nd7 stops Nxd4 because the pawn on  e5  will hang. }
6. O-O Ne7 7. Re1 Nc6
{ The tabiya of this variation. White has to decide now whether it is worthwhile to spend a move on a3 to stop the bishop manoeuver Bb4, Ba5 and Bc7 which puts even more pressure on  e5  . }
8. Nbd2 Bb4 9. a3 Ba5 10. b4 Bc7 { Defending  e5  will not be easy for White. }
*

