[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Various 5th Moves"]
[Black "Introduction to 5. Be3 and other 5th Moves"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6
{ There are a few alternatives to 5. Nf3 at move 5. But by far the most common is the Kupreichik variation 5. Be3. }
5. Be3
{ The most popular of the alternatives at move 5:      5.g3  Qa5  6.Nf3  Nxd4  This is Watson's suggestion. I like it quite a bit.    5.a3  f6  This is very similar to the 6. a3 f6 line with one key difference. While it does not make sense to avoid 6. Nf3 for White, Black can postpone Bd7 for the time being, essentially winning a tempo in many variations.    5.Be2  f6  Here exactly the same reasoning as after 5. a3 applies.     5.f4  Nh6  is fine for Black, followed by the usual moves: Qb6, cxd4 and Bd7.     5.Qg4  cxd4  This is good for Black. The pawn on  d4  will be difficult to defend after Qb6, Nh6 and Nf5. }
5... Qb6 6. Qd2 Bd7
{ 6. ...f6  7.Nf3   7.f4  Nh6  is good for Black   7.exf6  Nf6  is also good for Black. Queen and dark-squared bishop are awkwardly placed.  fxe5  8.Nxe5  Nf6  is also a good option for Black and in fact the suggestion in the repertoire.  For this introduction, I chose to make the alternative suggestion the mainline because I believe it is a safe and straightforward way to handle the Kupreichik variation. }
7. Nf3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Rc8 9. Nc3 Na5
{ Black will play Nc4 as soon as the bishop on  f1  has moved. This variation poses no problems for Black. This is the safe solution recommended, for instance, by Aagaard and Ntirlis. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Various 5th Moves"]
[Black "5. Be3 Kupreichik safe 1 Alt"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Be3 { The Kupreichik variation. } 5...
Qb6 6. Qd2 Bd7
{ Black plans to play cxd4, Rc8 and Na5-c4 in this order to make use of the placement of White's queen and dark-squared bishop. }
7. f4 Nh6
{ The standard response. The knight wants to go to  f5  , and after White has played f4, Nh6 is the correct path. Bxh6 is no longer possible, and the knight does not block the bishop as after Nge7. }
8. Nf3 Rc8 9. Be2 cxd4 10. Nxd4
{ 10.cxd4  Bb4  11.Nc3  Na5  is also a bit better for Black. } 10... Nxd4 11.
Bxd4 Bc5
{ If White exchanges on  c5  Black recaptures with the queen and gets the pawns on the queenside moving with a5, b5 and b4. }
*

