{ Watson's suggestion. Black threatens cxd4. } 6. Nd2 cxd4 7. Nb3
{ This was White's idea. Since Nb3 comes with tempo, White hopes to be able to stabilize the center. Unfortunately  (for White)  the knight on  b3  can be attacked immediately with a5 and a4. }
7... Qb6 8. cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 a5 10. Nf3
{ 10.a4  Bxd2  11.Nxd2  Nxd4  Black wins a pawn. } 10... a4 11. Bxb4 Qxb4+ 12.
Nbd2 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. Bb5+ Bd7 15. Qe2
{ 15.Bxd7  Kxd7  16.Qe2  Ne7  is also possible. But while the pawn on  e5  needs the protection of the queen, Qb5+ is not dangerous. If White does not play Qb5+ immediately, then Black also has no problems after, for instance, Nf5 and Rhc8. }
15... Bc6 { Black won a pawn. } *

