1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Be2 f6
{ This is similar to the mainlines where White plays Be2 one move later. The fact that Black does not need to play Bd7 immediately while White does not profit from postponing Nf3 gives Black additional options.  Whether Black can profit from these additional options is difficult to tell. }
6. Nf3 fxe5 7. dxe5 Nh6 8. O-O Nf7 9. Re1 Bd7
{ 9...g5  is also interesting but a bit risky. For instance,  10.Nxg5  is not so easy to refute.   9...Qc7  is certainly playable but I prefer to play the least committal move first. }
10. Na3 a6
{ 10. ...Qc7  11.Nb5  Qb8  12.c4  d4  13.Bd3  a6  14.Nd6+  is a promising pawn sacrifice by White. Playing a6 is safer. }
11. h3
{ 11.Bf4  g5  12.Bg3  h5  is not so pleasant for White. h3 prepares Bf4 by creating the escape on  h2  and also by waiting for the queen to move to  c7  from which it does not support  g5  any longer. }
11... Qc7 12. Bf4 Be7
{ The position is about equal. Black keeps all options open. Most likely Black will castle queenside followed by h5, g5 and g4. But O-O is still possible as well. }
*

