[Black "Introduction to rarely played 6th Moves"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7
{ The two most common alternatives to the main line here are 6. Be3 often transposing to the Kupreichik variation 5. Be3 and 6. Na3. }
6. Be3
{ Here the alternatives for White are:    6.Na3  f6  7.Bd3  cxd4  followed by Bb4, fxe5 and Nge7 and Black is fine. Black should avoid 'winning' the pawn on  a3  with cxd4, Bxa3 and Qa5. The dark squares in Black's camp can get very weak.    6.g3  Qb6  7.Bg2  cxd4  followed by Ne7 and Nf5 and I would prefer Black already.    6.Nbd2  cxd4  followed Qb6. If the knight goes to  b3  , Black can chase it away again with a5 and a4. If White stops the a-pawn with a4, then the square  b4  is weak. This motif is well-known from the Tarrasch variation. Here I like Black better as well. }
6... Qb6 7. Qd2
{ and now Black can choose between  - cxd4, transposing to the 'safe' variation against the Kupreichik variation,   - f6, fxe5 and Nh6 for a more unbalanced game. }
7... cxd4 { The plan f6, fxe5 and Nh6 works as well. } *

