[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. 6. dxc5"]
[Black "Introduction to 6. dxc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. dxc5
{ White wants to play Bd3. If White plays Bd3 immediately then White has to be ready to play the Milner-Barry gambit  (see the last chapter)  . Another idea of dxc5, besides preparing Bd3, is to use the b-pawn to dislodge the knight on  c6  with b4 and b5 in the fight for the square  e5  . Black's main plan is to eliminate the pawn on  e5  . Because White has played dxc5 Black can use the f-pawn to get rid of White's last remaining central pawn.   Depending on whether or not Black has played f6 already when White plays b4 there are two separate plans for Black. If White plays b4 after f6 then Black returns the bishop to  e7  to protect the king. If White plays b4 immediately then Black retreats the bishop to  b6  . Since Black's kingside is a bit weaker in this case, Black postpones f6 until after development is complete. }
6... Bxc5 7. b4
{ 7.Bd3  f6  8.b4  Be7  9.b5  Nxe5  10.Nxe5  fxe5  11.Qh5+  Kf8  12.Qxe5  Bf6  Here Black's plan is to play Ne7 and Kf7 to get the king to safety. The point to remember is that if White plays b4 after Black has already played f6 then Be7 is the safer choice  (see Black's 12th move)  . }
7... Bb6
{ The main ideas for Black now are  - don't play Nc4 without a good reason,  - play Qe7 and then double the rooks on the c-file,  - Bg5 can be answered with f6. }
*

