1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. b4 Bb6 8. b5
Na5 9. Bd3 Ne7
{ The order of the next moves does not matter so much. The two points to remember are   - don't play Nc4 unless there is a concrete reason - because otherwise White can solve his problems on the queenside with Nbd2  - don't play Qc7 because the goal is to eventually put the queen on  e7  and double the rooks on the c-file. }
10. O-O Rc8
{ Black's plan is straightforward:   - play Ng6, O-O then Qe7 and double the rooks on the c-file.   - Bg5 can be answered with f6.   - don't play Nc4 if White can answer Nbd2. }
11. a4 Ng6 12. Re1 O-O 13. Qc2 Qe7 14. Bg5 f6 15. exf6 gxf6 16. Bh6 Ne5
{ A multipurpose move. It removes the threat Bxg6, and it forces White to either accept a doubled pawn on f3 or to give Black a strong pawn center after Nxe5. The exchange is a small price to pay for this.   16...Rfe8 ?  17.Bxg6  hxg6  18.Qxg6+  would be better for White. }
17. Bxf8 Nxf3+ 18. gxf3 Qxf8 19. Kh1 Qh6 20. Rg1+ Kf7
{ The pawn on  h7  is safe because f5 traps the bishop. The position is unclear. Note that as soon as the knight moves away from  b1  Black can increase the pressure on c3 with Bd4. }
*

