1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. Bd3 f6 8. b4
Be7 9. b5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 fxe5 11. Qh5+ Kf8 12. Qxe5 Bf6
{ This move is the reason for preferring Be7 to Bb6. } 13. Qe2 Ne7 14. O-O Rc8
{ Originally, I intended to go with Aagaard & Ntirlis suggestion  14...Kf7  15.a4  Ng6  but now, as one of the beta testers pointed out,  16.Qh5!   16.Re1  Rhe8  was the only continuation given by Aagaard & Ntirlis  (is a problem.)  The move Rc8 is essentially the most flexible and useful waiting move I could find. It is still too early to commit either knight  (probably Ng6, but Nf5 may be better)  , queen  (probably Qc7, especially if Ng6 has been played, but Qb6+ may be better)  or king  (probably f7, but g8 may be better)  to a square. The rook puts pressure on c3  (when the knight moves, Rxc3 may be annoying for White)  .   That being said, Qc7 with the ideas Qe5 or Ng6 and Nf4 is also interesting. }
15. a4
{ White answers with a waiting move as well. The pawn on  b5  is now protected. White is now threatening f4 Nf5 / g4 because Nd4 is no longer a double attack as in the 15. f4 variation. }
15... e5
{ 15...Qc7  with the ideas  Qe5  or  Ng6  and  Nf4  is also playable.  Black doesn't play e5 on move 14 since in that case the unprotected square  c5  can become a problem. }
16. f3 Nf5 { Followed by Kf7 and Rhe8. The position is about equal. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. 6. a3"]
[Black "Introduction to 6. a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. a3
{ This move plans to stabilize the center with b4 and perhaps Bb2. } 6... f6
{ The most active and ambitious answer. But there are two good alternatives. Either of Nge7 and c4 can be played without having to remember any theory. Just look once at the corresponding informational variations, and you are good to go.  I use these moves when I don't want to bother with theory. }
7. Bd3
{ White's main response, preparing to castle and putting the bishop on a more active square than in the 6.Be2 line.   White's alternatives are:    7.b4  fxe5  8.b5  Nxd4  This is the line which initially attracted me to 6...f6. The point to remember here is that Black can, in spite of being a piece down, calmly complete his development before putting the central pawns in motion.     7.Bf4  Qb6  the standard answer to Bf4. }
7... Qc7 8. O-O O-O-O
{ The standard plan for Black in this position is h6 and f5, followed by g5.   Some guidelines for Black are:   - if White plays b4, Black should close off the queenside with c4,  - if White plays h4, Black should stop h5 with Be8 and possibly later play Bh5,  - if White plays Nh4, Black should protect  g6  with Be8, and if White continues with f4, then Be7 drives the knight back, and Bh5 can follow.   It is also possible to play g5 as a pawn sacrifice if the bishop is already on  e8  . The black queen can move to  h7  quickly and generate mating threats along the h-file. If White loses control over  e5  , then fxe5 is also an idea for Black. White's only chance for counterplay is on the queenside with b3. Usually Black should take and continue with Na5 to slow down c4. }
*

