[Black "6. ... c4 Info"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. a3 c4
{ is another option in case you like closed positions. The main point here is that Black can activate his light-squared bishop more quickly than in the corresponding Nc6, Qb6 lines: either with 7... Na5, 8... Bc6 !, 9... Qd7 and 10... Ba4 or with 8... Ne7, 9... Nc8, 10... Nb6 and 11... Ba4. Neither method is available with the queen on  b6  without additional moves. In these lines, move orders really don't matter much, so they are not suitable for the MoveTrainer. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. 6. a3"]
[Black "6. ... Nge7 Info"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. a3 Nge7 7. b4
{ 7.dxc5  Ng6  =+ } 7... cxd4 8. cxd4 Nf5
{ is another good if slightly dull option. After White protects  d4  with Be3 or Bb2, Black will play b5.   Then:  - if White takes on b5 with the bishop, then Ne5 regains the pawn with at least equality  - if White plays Nbd2 or Nc3, then a5 attacks the pawn on  b4  usually leading to the complete liquidation of the queenside again with positions Black has no trouble with.   So far I used this variation only in blitz games but have always had good positions going into the middlegame. }
*

