1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. a3 f6 7. Bd3
{ White's main response, preparing to castle and putting the bishop on a more active square than in the 6. Be2 line. }
7... Qc7
{ In this variation, Black does not need to hurry with taking on  e5  since exf6 is not a threat: both Nxf6 and gxf6 are a bit better for Black. }
8. exf6 { As usual, White taking on  f6  is nothing to worry about. } 8... gxf6
9. O-O
{ 9.b4  c4  followed by Bd6 is fine for Black.     9.dxc5  Bxc5  10.O-O  O-O-O  transposes to 9.O-O O-O-O 10.dxc5 Bxc5.    9.dxc5  Bxc5  10.c4  is possible, but here dxc4 followed by Ne5 or Ne5 directly are fine for Black. }
9... c4
{ White will find it more difficult to get counterplay on the queenside. Without c4, Black always has to keep the move c3-c4  (with or without a preceding dxc5)  in mind. }
10. Be2 O-O-O
{ Black can try to play for a quick e5 with Ne7 and Ng6. If White tries to nibble at the pawn chain with b3, Black can play Na5 to keep the queenside blocked. }
*

