*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. 6. a3"]
[Black "7. Bd3, 8. Bf4 1*"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. a3 f6 7. Bd3
{ White's main response, preparing to castle and putting the bishop on a more active square than in the 6. Be2 line. }
7... Qc7
{ In this variation, Black does not need to hurry with taking on  e5  since exf6 is not a threat: both Nxf6 and gxf6 are a bit better for Black. }
8. Bf4
{ With this move White increases the support for  e5  . If White's support is sufficient to enable him to always recapture with a piece on  e5  , even in case of multiple exchanges, then White is usually a bit better, because Black's weakness on  e6  is exposed to attacks by heavy pieces on the e-file. }
8... c4 9. Bc2 Nh6
{ The move h6 does not work so well here because Black has not castled yet, White has Bg6+. Castling long is possible but a bit inaccurate:   9...O-O-O  10.Nbd2  Nh6  11.Bg3  and now White can answer  11...Nf7?  with  12.exf6  and   11...Qb6?  with  12.b3.   9...O-O-O  10.Nbd2  h6  is possible but White can slow down Black's king side expansion with  11.h4.   9...g5?  is bad because Black's pawns on the kingside are quite weak after  10. Bg3;  10...f5?  is not possible while the g-pawn is hanging. }
10. Bxh6
{ This needs to be considered of course but is fine for Black. Also fine for Black is  10.Bg3  Qb6  because White has no convenient way to protect the b-pawn and  11.b3  is only good if  Nbd2  has already been played. }
10... gxh6 11. exf6 O-O-O 12. O-O Bd6
{ The pawn on  f6  will fall, and Black has the bishop pair and half open files against the king. This should at least make up for the doubled h-pawn. I prefer Black. }
*

