[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. a3 f6 7. Bd3
{ White's main response, preparing to castle and putting the bishop on a more active square than in the 6. Be2 line. }
7... Qc7
{ In this variation, Black does not need to hurry with taking on  e5  since exf6 is not a threat: both Nxf6 and gxf6 are a bit better for Black. }
8. Bf4
{ White tries to support  e5  with enough pieces so that in case of multiple exchanges on  e5  at the end White can recapture with a piece instead of a pawn. That would leave Black's weakness on  e6  exposed. }
8... c4 9. Bc2 Nh6
{ The move h6 does not work so well here because Black has not castled yet, White has Bg6+. Castling long is possible but a bit inaccurate:   9...O-O-O  10.Nbd2  Nh6  11.Bg3  and now White can answer  11...Nf7?  with  12.exf6  and   11...Qb6?  with  12.b3.   9...O-O-O  10.Nbd2  h6  is possible but White can slow down Black's king side expansion with  11.h4.   9...g5?  is bad because Black's pawns on the kingside are quite weak after  10. Bg3;  10...f5?  is not possible while the g-pawn is hanging. }
10. Nbd2 Nf7 11. Bg3 fxe5 12. Nxe5 Nfxe5 13. dxe5 O-O-O
{ Black plays Be7 next and can start attacking with g5. Kb8 should probably also be played at some point. Another move to consider here is Bc5  (one of the benefits of playing c4)  . }
