1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. a3 f6 7. Bb5 Qb6
{ Black has many options here. I like Qb6 because it forces White to decide what to do with the bishop on b5 without committing Black to any particular setup. }
8. Bxc6 Qxc6 9. O-O Ne7 { Black plans to put more pressure on e5 with Ng6. }
10. dxc5 { 10.h4  Rc8  followed by Nf5 looks fine for Black as well. } 10...
Qxc5 11. Be3 Qc7 12. Bd4 f5
{ The position is roughly equal. Black can continue with Nc6 or Ng6      followed by Be7 and O-O. }
