[White "9. 6. Be2"]
[Black "Introduction to 6. Be2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Be2
{ A neutral non-committal developing move. The only possible disadvantage is that it blocks the e-file and that moving to the more active square will cost a tempo.   The blocking of the e-file is the main reason why after 6. Be2 Black's answer f6 is possible but after 6. Bd3 it is not. }
6... f6
{ Here Nge7 is a good alternative, but to keep in line with the other variations, I chose f6 as the repertoire move. }
7. O-O { 7.Bf4  cxd4  8.cxd4  g5  is already better for Black. } 7... fxe5 8.
Nxe5
{ 8.dxe5  Qc7  The main ideas for Black are straightforward. Black should   -castle queenside  -keep the center closed with d4 if White plays c4  -answer Na3 with a6  -put pressure on  e5  by playing Nh6, Nf7, Be7, g5 and possibly h5 and g4  -try to play Nh6 after White has committed to Bf4 because then Bxh6 will lose a tempo  -answer a3 with c4 if White hasn't played c4 yet }
8... Nxe5 9. dxe5 Qc7
{ Black's next moves will be O-O-O and Qxe5 if possible. These lines are quite important since they show up rather often and move orders matter here. }
*

