cxd4
{ If Black does not take on  d4  , then White can consider playing dxc5 and c4. }
9. cxd4 Bd6 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Bd3 Be8 12. Qe2 Bf7
{ Black can choose one of several different setups. For example: a6, Qc7 and Rae8, or Rfe8 and Bh5, or even a6, Bc7 and Qd6.   The position is in fact very similar to positions arising from the 3. ... Nf6 variation in the Tarrasch, but Black is about 2-3 tempi ahead: White's bishop needed two moves to get to  d3  and Black's queen did not have to move to  c7  to avoid the exchange of the dark-squared bishops. Finally, the queen on  e2  is misplaced and will have to move again. Because of this Black already managed to get the light-squared bishop to  f7  from where it can move to  h5  at any time. }
