1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Be2 f6 7. O-O
{ The best move. } 7... fxe5 { This clarifies the situation in the center. } 8.
dxe5
{ The disadvantage of this move is that the knight can quickly become a target. Either for the g-pawn: h6, g5, g4 or Nh6, Nf7, Be7, g5, g4 or for a rook: Rxf3 and Nxe5 usually give Black enough compensation for the exchange. }
8... Qc7 9. Re1
{ Indirectly protecting  e5  with the discovered check on  h5  . } 9... O-O-O
10. c4 d4 11. Bd3 Nh6 { Be7 first is also good. } 12. Bxh6 gxh6 13. a3 Kb8
{ The next few moves Kb8, Be8 and Rg8 can be played in any order.  I believe it is a good idea to include Kb8 as a preparatory move. One reason for this is that White is likely to play b4 at some point, and if Black takes, the a-file will be opened. Having protected  a7  in advance will be useful in that case. Another minor point is that White does not have the dark-squared bishop any longer, so placing the king on a dark square feels safer to me. In the end, I think it is merely a decision based on experience, in other words, I have lost enough games where I kept my king on  c8  . }
14. Nbd2 Be8 15. Be4 Rg8 *

