1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Be2 f6 7. O-O
{ The best move. } 7... fxe5 { This clarifies the situation in the center. } 8.
Nxe5 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Qc7 10. Bf4 O-O-O
{ Black castles to prepare h6 and g5. After the immediate h6 White has Bh5+. }
11. b4 Ne7
{ 11...c4  now is not good. White can play  12.a4  followed by   Na3  (, Nb5 and Be3 forcing Black to move the a- or b-pawn. After that White's attack on the queenside will be much faster than anything Black can generate on the kingside.) }
12. Nd2 { 12.bxc5  Ng6  is fine for Black. } 12... Kb8
{ Here  12...c4  is playable in my opinion. Have a look at ML  10.Bf4  11.b4  4 Info for details. The main reason why Black can get away with playing   c4  ( here are:   )  (i)  (White cannot play )  Na3  ( any longer, )  (ii)  (Black has not played )  Ng6  ( yet, a quick )  h6  ( and )  g5  ( is still possible.)   12...Ng6  is premature. After  13.Bg3  it is not easy for Black to generate counterplay on the kingside. White can stabilize the center with  f4  after which piece pressure against the e-pawn is pointless. Attacking the f-pawn with  h6  and  g5  is possible but to do so Black has to retreat with the knight, essentially wasting two tempi. }
13. Nf3 Ng6
{ Here  13...c4  may be playable but I don't like Black's position after  14.Ng5.  White is threatening   Bg4  ( and also )  Nf7  ( and )  Nd6  (.) }
14. Bg3
{ Édouard gives only   14.Be3  Ka8  with a reasonable position for Black. I agree. However, I like Rc8 instead of Ka8 even better. In case White takes on  c5  , the rook move is more useful. If White does not take on  c5  then Ka8 can be played next. }
14... cxb4
{ How about  14...c4  now? I think White is better after  15.Ng5   15.Qd2  followed by   Qe3  (, )  a4  (, )  Nd4  ( and )  Nb5  ( is also good)  Bc8  16.Bh5.  Black's knight on  g6  is a convenient target for White.  In either case I would prefer to be White. }
15. cxb4 Bxb4 16. Rb1 Ba5
{ White has compensation for the pawn. But Black's king is safe enough after Ka8. }
