1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Be2 f6 7. O-O
{ The best move. } 7... fxe5 { This clarifies the situation in the center. } 8.
Nxe5 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Qc7 10. Bf4 O-O-O
{ Black castles to get ready for h6 and g5. The move h6 has to be prepared because   10. ...h6  11.Bh5+  is good for White. }
11. a4
{ Given as interesting by the Sveshnikovs. Édouard suggested the following setup for Black. }
11... Kb8
{ White plans to attack on the queenside. That makes it necessary to move the king to  b8  to be able to counter threats on the b-file with Ka8 and to free the square  c8  for the rook. }
12. Na3 c4
{ 12...a6 ?!  13.b4  Although  a6  stops Nb5, it is too dangerous here. The problem is that it gives White a way to open lines on the queenside with b5. }
13. b4 { 13.b3  cxb3  is the same. } 13... cxb3 14. Qxb3 Bc5
{ The point of c4. The square  c5  can be used by the Black pieces now. } 15.
Nc2 Ne7 16. Nb4 Ka8
{ Here we see why playing Kb8 was a good idea. The king is quite safe in the corner. Rc8 has become possible, as well. With Black controlling the c-file and putting pressure on  c3  , it will be much more difficult for White to start an attack on the queenside. }
*

