1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Be2 f6 7. O-O
{ The best move. } 7... fxe5 { This clarifies the situation in the center. } 8.
Nxe5 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Qc7 10. Bf4 O-O-O 11. Na3 Ne7 12. Nb5 Bxb5 13. Bxb5
{ The Sveshnikovs think that 'the two bishops promise White a pleasant game', but I think if anyone is better here it is Black. }
13... Ng6 14. Bg3
{ White wants to keep the bishop pair.   14.Bg5  Be7  15.Bxe7  Nxe7  is possible, but here I would prefer Black. It is not so easy for White to open lines on the queenside  (b4 can be answered with c4, and c4 with a6 and dxc4)  while Black can improve his position with Nf5, Rhf8 and perhaps Kb8. }
14... h5 15. h3 Kb8
{ The engines seem to like  15...c4  but after  16.b3  a6  17.Ba4  h4  (b5 is tempting but too risky)  18.Bh2  Nxe5  19.bxc4  dxc4  20.Qe1  Bd6  21.Bxe5  Bxe5  the position looks unclear to me. I like  Kb8  to keep my options open. }
