[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. 6. Be2"]
[Black "ML 11. Re1 2*"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Be2 f6 7. O-O
{ The best move. } 7... fxe5 { This clarifies the situation in the center. } 8.
Nxe5 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Qc7 10. c4 O-O-O 11. Re1
{ This is one of the main lines of the 6. Be2 f6 variation. It looks a bit dangerous but Black can take the pawn on e5. }
11... Qxe5 12. Bf3
{ 12.Nc3  Nf6  and   12.cxd5  exd5  will very likely transpose to some other line in this chapter. }
12... Qf5
{ Here as well it looks as if  f5  is the best square for the queen. } 13. Nc3
{ 13.cxd5  exd5  transposes to 11.cxd5  Qxe5  12.Bf3  exd5  13.Re1  Qf5. }
13... Nf6 14. Qb3
{ A new move in this position, first, as far as I know, suggested by Édouard. White targets the pawn on  b7   . Instead  14.cxd5  exd5  transposes to 11.cxd5  Qe5  12.Nc3  Nf6  13.Bf3  exd5  14.Re1  Qf5. }
14... Bc6
{ 14. ...g5  15.cxd5  g4  16.Bd1!  exd5  17.Bc2!  is, unfortunately, a bit better for White. }
15. Nb5 Bxb5
{ 15. ...Kb8  16.a4  is also interesting, but Black has to be quite careful to avoid various tactics based on checks on the diagonal  h2  -  b8  . Since it is not so easy to find  (and to remember)  the route to safety here, I chose Bxb5 as the mainline. }
16. Qxb5 g5 17. cxd5 g4
{ It is important to chase the bishop away from  f3  . } 18. Be2 Nxd5
{ Black has several other reasonable moves here, for instance, a6 or Rxd5. But I think Nxd5 is the most natural move here. }
19. Bd3 Qf6 20. Qa4 Nb4
{ 20. ...Rg8  21.Qxa7  Bd6  is also possible but allowing  Qxa7  may not be everybody's cup of tea. }
21. Be4 Kb8
{ White has compensation for the pawn but not more. Black's knight can always return to  d5  to stabilize the position, possibly returning the pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. 6. Be2"]
[Black "ML 11. Re1 3 Info"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Be2 f6 7. O-O
{ The best move. } 7... fxe5 { This clarifies the situation in the center. } 8.
Nxe5 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Qc7 10. c4 O-O-O 11. Re1
{ This is one of the main lines of the 6. Be2 f6 variation. It looks a bit dangerous but Black can take the pawn on e5. }
11... Qxe5 12. Bf3
{ 12.Nc3  Nf6  and   12.cxd5  exd5  will very likely both transpose to the final position of this line  (moves 12-14 can be played almost in any order)  . }
12... Qf5
{ Here as well it looks as if  f5  is the best square for the queen. } 13. Nc3
Nf6 14. Qb3
{ A new move in this position, first, as far as I know, suggested by Édouard. White targets the pawn on  b7  . Instead   14.cxd5  exd5  transposes to 11. cxd5 Qe5 12. Nc3 Nf6 13. Bf3 exd5 14. Re1 Qf5. }
14... Bc6
{ 14. ...g5  15.cxd5  g4  16.Bd1!  exd5  17.Bc2!  is unfortunately a bit better for White. }
15. Nb5 Kb8 16. a4
{ White prepares to recapture with the a-pawn to open the a-file. } 16... Rd7
{ A mysterious rook manoeuver. This move has two main purposes. It enables Black to play b6 to defend the pawn on  a7  in case ...Bxb5 and axb5 have been played. It also covers c7 against possible threats on the  h2  -  b8  diagonal. If there were no bishop on  f3  , the move Qg3+ would be very strong without a rook on  d7  . }
17. Qe3 { Attacks the weak pawn on  e6  . } 17... Bxb5
{ Black has problems with defending the pawn on  e6  . For example:   17. ...Re7  18.Qxc5  and White wins. }
18. axb5 Bd6 19. h3
{ This move is not as innocent as it looks. One threat is g4 to push back the Black queen.     19.Qa3 ?  b6  shows why the move Rd7 was necessary. Here Black is better. Without the rook on  d7  White would win.     19.Qe6  Re8  20.Qxe8+  Nxe8  21.Rxe8+  Kc7  22.Bd2   22.Bxd5  Bxh2+  23.Kxh2  Qh5+  22...Re7  23.Ba5+  b6  24.Bxb6+  Kxb6  25.Ra6+  Kc7  26.Ra7+ =  is a line given by Édouard. In this line Black has other options at move 22, for instance Be5, but they only lead to positions which are highly unclear. }
19... Re8
{ 19. ...h5  20.Qxe6  Re8  21.Qxe8  Nxe8  22.Rxe8  Kc7  23.Bxd5  is a minimally improved version of 19. Qxe6. But White has other options at move 20. For example, 20. Bd2 or 20. b4 d4 21. Qb3. The only conclusion I could come up with is highly unclear. }
20. g4 Qg6
{ The position is unclear. Engines are happy with the Black side. I am not. White spent two tempi on h3 and g4, but Black's moves Re8 and Qg6 also did not improve the situation on the queenside. In fact, one big difference is that the queen can no longer get back to the queenside via the fifth rank, which improves White's attacking chances. }
21. b4 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. 6. Bd3 (the Milner-Barry Gambit)"]
[Black "Introduction to the Milner-Barry Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Bd3
{ White is more or less forced to sacrifice a pawn } 6... cxd4 7. cxd4 Qb6 8.
O-O
{ The alternatives are not impressive.     8.Be2  Nge7  White loses a tempo with Be2, but the resulting positions are about equal.      8.Bc2  Nb4  9.Bb3 ?  Qa6!  Bc2 tries to keep the bishop on the  b1  -  h7  diagonal but runs into problems after the straightforward Nb4. If the bishop escapes to  b3  then Black is already better. }
8... Nxd4 9. Nbd2
{ This the new mainline. Alternatives are the not entirely correct but dangerous Ng5 and the old mainline Nxd4.        9.Ng5  Nc6 !  Ng5 is probably incorrect. But it is also not very easy to deal with over the board. Black's best answer is to retreat with the knight to  c6  to put immediate pressure on the pawn on  e5  .   General principles don't work well in this variation but two rules of thumb which at least worked for me so far are   - use Nh6 to defend  f7   - let White take on  h7  if he wants to, often Nb4 is a good answer to Nxh7 and Bxh7 can often be answered with g6 or Be7.     9.Nxd4  Qxd4  10.Nc3  a6 !  11.Qe2  Ne7  12.Kh1  Nc6  13.f4  Nb4  This is the old mainline. The knight manoeuver Ne7, Nc6 and Nb4 is timed perfectly. Saving the bishop by retreating to  b1  runs into Qc4. Protecting it with Rd1 gives Black time for Bc5 and Qf2, which leads to endgames advantageous for Black.  Key points are:  - in this line  (and in this line only)  answer Nc3 with a6  (needed to stop Nb5)   - if White chooses some other setup after move 10, inviting Black to take the pawn on  e5  , then a good rule of thumb is that it is safe to take the pawn on  e5  with the queen    + if either Ne7 has been played already or     + if White cannot attack the queen with Bf4 immediately afterwards. }
9... Bc5 10. b4
{ If Black takes on  b4  , then White hopes to either pin the bishop to the queen, or, to chase away the queen and take on  b7  . }
10... Nxf3+ 11. Nxf3 Qxb4
{ Don't take with the bishop. If you do, White is better after Rb1. } 12. Rb1
Qa4
{ This is the last key manoeuver to remember. Black is willing to return one of the two extra pawns to exchange queens. }
*

