1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Bd3 cxd4 7. cxd4 Qb6 8. O-O
Nxd4 9. Nxd4 Qxd4 10. Nc3 a6 11. Qe2 Ne7 12. Rd1
{ White threatens a discovered attack by the rook but this attack is not a problem since Black can counter by attacking  e5  . }
12... Nc6
{ Now f4 is impossible and Re1 a bit pointless so giving up  e5  is the only reasonable choice for White. }
13. Bxa6 Qxe5 14. Qxe5 Nxe5 15. Bxb7
{ Retreating the bishop is safer  (and better)  , but still, the resulting positions are better for Black. Taking on  b7  is weaker, but not so easy to refute. The following variation is quite long but essentially forced. }
15... Ra7 16. Bxd5 exd5 17. Re1 f6 18. f4 Bc5+ 19. Kh1 d4 20. Nb1 O-O 21. fxe5
fxe5 22. Nd2 Bb4 23. Rxe5 Rf2 24. Kg1 Rxd2 25. Bxd2 Bxd2 *

