[White "10. 6. Bd3 (the Milner-Barry Gambit)"]
[Black "11.Qxf3 15...Rac8 16.Ng5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Bd3 cxd4 7. cxd4 Qb6 8. O-O
Nxd4 9. Nbd2 Bc5 10. b4 Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3
{ A move suggested by Solakian in his course 'The Audacious      Milner-Barry Gambit'. }
11... Qxb4
{ This move is easier to play than the alternative Bd4.   11...Bd4  12.Qg3  Bxa1  13.Qxg7  Bxe5  14.Qxe5  f6  15.Qh5+  Kf8  Although this line is certainly playable for Black it is      dangerous, especially when you are not well prepared. }
12. Rb1 { 12.Qg3  Ne7  13.Rb1  Qa4  transposes to 12.Rb1 Qa413.Qg3 Ne7 } 12...
Qa4 13. Qg3
{ Here we see the reason for Qxf3. Black does not threaten to exchange queens on d1 so White can take the pawn on b7 while keeping the queens on the board.   13.Rxb7  Ne7  14.Qg3  O-O  transposes. }
13... Ne7 14. Rxb7
{ White regains one of the two sacrificed pawns.   14.Nb3  Bb6  transposes to 13. Nb3 }
14... O-O 15. Nf3 Rac8
{ Solokian only considers   15...Ng6  16.h4!  and   15...Rfb8  16.Qh3!  in his course. I believe both Rac8 and a6 are safer options. Black keeps f7 protected and does not offer White an easy target on g6. }
16. Ng5 Nf5 17. Bxf5
{ 17.Qh3  h6  18.g4  hxg5  19.gxf5  g4  is better for Black. } 17... exf5 18.
e6 fxe6 19. Bb2
{ 19.Nxe6  Rf7  20.Nxc5  Rxc5  is equal. Black's extra pawn does not     matter and White's attack is stuck as well. Black can stabilize      his position with Rc8 and Bc6 or Qc6. }
19... Qc6 20. Nxe6 Rf7 21. Nxc5 Qxc5
{ Again with a balanced position. Black can strengthen his position     with f4 and Re8. As long as he does not touch the g-pawn Black is      not worse. }
*

