[White "10. 6. Bd3 (the Milner-Barry Gambit)"]
[Black "11.Qxf3 15...Rac8 16.Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Bd3 cxd4 7. cxd4 Qb6 8. O-O
Nxd4 9. Nbd2 Bc5 10. b4 Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3
{ A move suggested by Solakian in his course 'The Audacious      Milner-Barry Gambit'. }
11... Qxb4
{ This move is easier to play than the alternative Bd4.   11...Bd4  12.Qg3  Bxa1  13.Qxg7  Bxe5  14.Qxe5  f6  15.Qh5+  Kf8  Although      this line is certainly playable for Black it is dangerous, especially      when you are not well prepared. }
12. Rb1 { 12.Qg3  Ne7  13.Rb1  Qa4  transposes to 12.Rb1 Qa413.Qg3 Ne7 } 12...
Qa4 13. Qg3
{ Here we see the reason for Qxf3. Black does not threaten to exchange queens on d1 so White can take the pawn on b7 while keeping the queens on the board.   13.Rxb7  Ne7  14.Qg3  O-O  transposes. }
13... Ne7 14. Rxb7
{ White regains of of the two sacrificed pawns.   14.Nb3  Bb6  transposes to 13. Nb3 }
14... O-O 15. Nf3 Rac8
{ Solokian only considers   15...Ng6  16.h4!  and   15...Rfb8  16.Qh3!  in his course. I believe both Rac8 and a6 are safer options. Black keeps f7 protected and does not offer White an easy target on g6. }
16. Be3 Bxe3 17. fxe3 Ng6
{ Black does not need to fear h4 because the counterplay with Rc3 is      quick enough. }
18. h4 Rc3 19. h5
{ 19.Bb1  Bb5  20.Rxb5  Qxb5  21.h5  Qc5  22.hxg6  Qxe3+  23.Qf2  Qxf2+  24.Rxf2  Rc1+  25.Rf1  Rxf1+  26.Kxf1  hxg6  and the two pieces are no match for      Black's rook and three pawns. }
19... Rxd3 20. hxg6 fxg6
{ This is the safer option. Black activates the rook. WIth two extra      pawns Black does not need to worry about the slightly damaged pawn      structure. }
21. Qg5 Re8 { stopping Qe7. Black can play Rd1 or h6 next. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. 6. Bd3 (the Milner-Barry Gambit)"]
[Black "11. Qxf3 15...a6 info"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Bd3 cxd4 7. cxd4 Qb6 8. O-O
Nxd4 9. Nbd2 Bc5 10. b4 Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3
{ A move suggested by Solakian in his course 'The Audacious Milner-Barry Gambit'. }
11... Qxb4 12. Rb1 Qa4 13. Qg3 Ne7 14. Rxb7
{ White regains one of the two sacrificed pawns. } 14... O-O 15. Nf3 a6
{ with the idea Bb5 } 16. Be3
{ 16.Bxh7+  Kxh7  17.Ng5+  Kg8  18.Qh3  Qc2  19.Rxd7  Rad8  -+  Black is      better. He has the better bishop and a protected passed pawn. The rook     on d7 will likely be exchanged soon and White's attack cannot be      easily strengthened because the black queen cannot be forced to leave      the b1-h7 diagonal.   16.Ng5  Ng6  17.h4  Bb5  18.h5  Qh4  19.Qxh4  Nxh4  20.Bxh7+  Kh8  21.Re1  Rab8  22.Rxb8  Rxb8  23.Bb1  Kg8  is about equal. }
16... Bxe3 17. fxe3 Ng6 18. Ng5
{ 18.h4  Bb5  19.Bxb5  axb5  20.Nd4  Qa6  21.Rxb5  h6  =+  stopping h5 and h6      by White, }
18... Bb5 19. Qh3
{ 19.Bxg6  fxg6  20.Rxf8+  Rxf8  21.h3  Bd7  The position is still unclear      but I prefer Black because of the extra pawn and the better pawn      structure. But White does have some compensation.  22.Qg4  Qc6 }
19... h6 20. Bxg6 fxg6 21. Qxe6+ Kh8 22. Rxf8+ Rxf8
{ looks dangerous but White has to be precise to keep the position      equal. }
23. h3
{ Surprisingly the only move for White.   23.Nf7+  Kh7  24.h3  Qe4  -+  The pawn on e3 cannot be defended.   23.h4  hxg5  24.hxg5  Rf1+  25.Kh2  Qh4+ }
23... Qa3 24. Nf7+ Kh7 25. Qb6 d4 26. Qxd4 { 26.exd4  Qc1+  27.Kh2  Qf4+ }
26... Bc6 27. Rc7 Qxa2 28. Ng5+
{ 28.Rxc6  Rxf7  29.e6  is not a problem because Black has  29...Qf2+  30.Kh2  Rf3  followed by Rxe3. }
28... hxg5 29. Rxc6 Qb1+ 30. Kh2 Rf1
{ and White's king has to come out into the open. } *

